[FORMATTING RULES]

* ATS-friendly Markdown only
* single-column structure
* standard section headings only
* no tables
* no columns
* no icons
* no images
* no decorative symbols
* no square brackets
* use blank lines between sections
* keep spacing clean and easy to scan

[SUMMARY RULES]
Summary is required.

Write 2 to 3 sentences only.

The Summary must:

* establish a market-facing role aligned to the target job
* state supported years of experience
* name the strongest supported tools, platforms, frameworks, systems, workflows, or domain areas relevant to the target function
* highlight the kind of value delivered, such as quality, automation, reliability, scalability, governance, release readiness, analytics, modernization, platform ownership, product delivery, or operational efficiency

The Summary must not:

* read like a generic self-description
* use filler such as results-driven, team player, self-starter, passionate, proven track record, dynamic professional, strong communicator
* include unsupported claims
* force metrics

Every sentence in the Summary must contain at least one of:

* target role or specialization
* named tool, platform, framework, workflow, or domain
* delivery scope
* meaningful technical, operational, or business impact area

The Summary must reflect the target function first, not the candidate’s broader background.

[SKILLS RULES]

* Include only relevant hard skills supported by the profile.
* Prioritize skills by target-role relevance.
* Use 4 to 6 compact category lines.
* Format each line exactly like:
  Category: skill 1, skill 2, skill 3
* The first 1 to 2 categories should reflect the target function when helpful.
* Prefer specific tools, platforms, systems, languages, frameworks, and concrete methodologies over vague labels.
* Expand umbrella platforms when useful for ATS.
* Do not list soft skills as standalone skills.

[EXPERIENCE RULES]

* List roles in reverse chronological order.
* For each role, use this exact heading format:
  Job Title | Company | Month YYYY - Month YYYY | Location
* Preserve company names, dates, and locations exactly.
* The job title may be normalized only when it improves market clarity without overstating seniority.
* Use 3 to 6 bullets per role based on recency, relevance, and available evidence.
* Give the most depth to the 2 to 3 most recent and most relevant roles.
* Do not add filler bullets.

[LENGTH AND DEPTH]
For experienced candidates, recent and relevant roles must be developed deeply enough to justify the candidate’s level.

* Do not compress important roles into shallow duty lists.
* Show enough detail to prove ownership, workflow complexity, tools, outputs, collaboration, and outcomes.
* Recent roles should be the main evidence for target-role fit.

[WEAK ROLES PREVENTION]
A role is weak and must be rewritten if:

* it mostly describes duties instead of accomplishments
* it could apply to many unrelated professionals
* it does not show role-specific workflows
* it lacks enough scope or depth for the candidate’s level
* it mentions tools without explaining what was done with them
* it reads like broad adjacent experience instead of the target function

[TARGET-FUNCTION WORKFLOW EVIDENCE]
Use the evidence bucket that matches the JD and the profile.

Examples:

* QA: test plans, test suites, manual regression, automation support, defect triage, JIRA, reproduction steps, screenshots, SQL validation, SOPs, release readiness, deployment verification, post-release checks, edge-case testing
* Data: SQL, ETL, validation, reconciliation, reporting, dashboards, schema understanding, data quality, pipelines, data operations
* AI or ML: Python, model training, evaluation, inference, deployment, experiment tracking, ML pipelines, MLOps
* Backend: APIs, services, databases, integrations, observability, runtime operations, scalability, reliability
* Frontend: UI features, React, TypeScript, JavaScript, accessibility, API integration, performance
* Mobile: Swift, SwiftUI, UIKit, testing, release workflows, performance
* Microsoft enterprise: Dynamics 365, Power Platform, Power Apps, Power Automate, Power BI, reporting, governance, administration, automation
* Product or business systems: ticketing, workflow configuration, reporting, user support, rollout, documentation, cross-functional delivery

Do not force unrelated role-family evidence.

[EXPERIENCE BULLETS]
Each bullet must:

* start with a strong action verb
* include at least one concrete anchor such as a named tool, platform, workflow, artifact, API, report, model, dashboard, dataset, service, release step, ticket type, or business outcome
* show specific ownership, contribution, validation, delivery, or improvement
* stay concise and readable
* sound believable for the candidate’s level

Use this shape when possible:
action + scope + tool or workflow or system + outcome or operational or business effect

Each bullet should show at least two of these when supported:

* what was built, tested, validated, owned, automated, documented, analyzed, or delivered
* what workflow, system, release step, process, ticket, report, or user journey was involved
* what tool, platform, method, or data source was used
* what changed, improved, was verified, or mattered

Include communication and teamwork through concrete actions when relevant, such as:

* translating user feedback into tickets
* documenting SOPs or release steps
* clarifying requirements
* triaging issues with developers
* coordinating releases or rollouts
* partnering with operators, product, support, QA, or business teams

Avoid bullets that:

* could fit almost any professional at almost any company
* sound like copied JD text
* only describe tasks without scope or outcomes
* mention tools without explaining what was done with them
* rely on vague phrases like stakeholders, enterprise clients, business workflows, technical support, actionable insights, operational performance unless the actual workflow, artifact, system, release step, or user group is named

[ACTION VERB RULES]
Use strong verbs such as:
Architected, Built, Designed, Developed, Implemented, Delivered, Automated, Integrated, Optimized, Deployed, Refactored, Launched, Configured, Administered, Migrated, Monitored, Resolved, Validated, Verified, Tested, Streamlined, Secured, Documented, Standardized

Avoid weak or vague openers such as:
Helped, Assisted, Supported, Worked on, Responsible for, Participated in, Involved in, Used, Handled

Vary verbs and sentence openings across bullets.

[METRICS RULES]

* Use metrics only when clearly supported and meaningful.
* Do not fabricate numbers.
* Do not force metrics into weak places.
* Prefer a natural mix of qualitative and quantitative bullets.
* If no defensible metric exists, show scope, technical depth, ownership, workflow complexity, operational impact, or business effect instead.

[EDUCATION RULES]
Use:
School | Degree | Years | Location

Keep it simple and ATS-friendly.

[PROJECTS OR CERTIFICATIONS]
Include these sections only when clearly relevant to the JD and supported by the profile.

[COVER LETTER RULES]
After the resume, generate a concise tailored cover letter for the same role.

* Keep it professional and specific.
* Connect the candidate background to the role clearly.
* Highlight relevant experience and business value.
* Do not invent facts.
* Do not use placeholders.

